eventName: Ray's Thank You to Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
My names Ray lindridge 56 years old father of 3 older sons 24,33,35 married for 35 years and new grandfather to a gorgeous 11 week granddaughter and very recently estranged. 
March 2019 i suffered   a devastating Stroke leaving me paralysed temporarily left side along with some other physical and cognitive challenges ..and am  now  registered disabled i am ultimately a survivor,and with the love of my family I have managed to regain some kind of normal life a very new life and certainly not one I invisageď but   luckily ,I  am stroke Survivor
Homeless  for sure but a survivor none the less
March 2020 i was diagnosed  with prostrate cancer 
Tomorrow 9am ish i will Park my motibility car (home)near to bognor regis pier and start my 50 Day Challenge to walk as far as I can whilst living in my car to raise as much cash on justgiving for 3 charities who have helped my family and myself enormously during this last 21 months along with another charity I hold very dear eg.
Stroke association  Lincolnshire
Headway Lincolnshire 
Macmillans 
And finally the Newfoundland club of Great Britain(welfare)


Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and secure. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs.

story:
On Friday 11th of December our dad's fight against cancer finally came to an end with his passing.

Our dad was a very strong man and fought this terrible illness all the way to the end and when it came he was surrounded by the family he loves and in return loved him.

We have set up this page to hopefully help provide some help to the people at McMillan who cared for my dad and treated him with the respect he deserved even in his final days but also because with our dad not being fond of flowers we believe this is what he would want.

We will all miss him so much every day of our lives, we just wish he knew how much he was loved and respected, not just by family but by friends and colleagues too.

story:
This page was set up in memory of my mother who sadly passed away on 8th December from cancer.  In her memory I am collecting donations for the local palliative care team based in Ashington, with all donations going direct to them, this was my mother’s wishes.

This team were absolutely amazing and the care and continued support they offer is second to none and we could not have managed the last 9 months without their support. The money raised will go directly to the Macmillan team based in Ashington and be used to fund care packages and essential personal care items for those in need in these desperate times we currently live in.

I know everyone is struggling financially at this time so ANY donations will be gratefully received and go a long way to helping this fabulous charity and the tireless work they do. I personally want to say special thanks to Helen, my mam’s Macmillan nurse who was, and still is brilliant.

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

eventName: In memory of Kathryn Joyce  Ashton
story:
It is with great sadness that Chris, Helen & Holly Ashton inform you of the passing of their much loved wife and mum Kathryn Joyce Ashton.

Kathryn passed away on Friday 11th December 2020 following complications due to Covid-19.

As the funeral date approaches (30th December 2020), the family would kindly encourage donations rather than flowers. 

Macmillan Cancer Support was a charity very close to Kathryn's heart as the nurses helped the family immensely when Chris Ashton was unwell. Kathryn never forgot about the support and comfort the Macmillan staff provided, hence we'd really appreciate any donations in her memory to this deserving cause.

With thanks & best wishes,

Chris, Helen & Holly Ashton

story:
As with many others 2020 has been the strangest of years, with highs, lows and everything in between. As a family we have been closer, and got used to being confined in the house and not travelling anywhere.

One positive consequence is that I dusted off the indoor bike and have been slowly but surely trying to return to fitness. Having lost approaching 20kgs I am now able to cycle, further and longer than I have ever done previously.

Over the past few months I have been trying to raise the kms
covered each week, and I have become a bit of a Zwift Addict (the virtual cycling experience). One group that helped me on this journey is the SZR (Swedish ZwiftRiders Group), and I have decided to take on my largest cycling challenge of my life and am joining them on an epic 300+km ride this Saturday the 19th, that they have organised starting at 7am.

SZR Endurance Ride Category D  www.zwift.com/events/view/1365585

The Swedish Group are fundraising for Barncancerfonden which
is a Swedish Charity that helps and contribute to paediatric cancer research with the aim of eradicating childhood cancer.

https://www.barncancerfonden.se/en/i-want-to-donate/donate-to-event/?activityId=1309504426

As you know I have decided to try and raise some money for Macmillan Cancer.  If you are interested in how the crazy ride goes then let me know and I will send you an update after the event. I am anticipating that the ride may take approximately 12 hours, so wish me luck.

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. So whatever cancer throws your way, we’re right right there with you.

charity.name: St John Ambulance
eventName: Supporting St John In the fight against COVID-19
story:
This winter may be our toughest yet

We need your help to continue our support for the NHS and ambulance service in these months ahead.

This winter, St John people will be supporting ambulances and hospitals across England. We’ll also be providing extra help – such as our falls service for the elderly and drop-in clinics for the homeless – in local communities.

We are also preparing for the biggest deployment of our volunteers, as we prepare to help deliver the vaccine against COVID-19 across the country.

We will post regular updates of the things we have been doing, and will continue to raise money to help support our operations during our deployment in the fight against COVID-19!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
On 3rd October 2020, my dad went into surgery for a triple heart bypass after being diagnosed with congenital heart disease earlier in the year. All was going well in his recovery until he suffered complications almost 2 weeks post-op. Dad endured so much and put up such a fight whilst in hospital for nearly 2 months. Dad was rushed into hospital from home and it was confirmed he had sepsis of the blood, pneumonia and was later diagnosed as having had a stroke due to an infection called 'Endocarditis' which is fatal for people with prosthetic heart valves and dad had just had one fitted less than two weeks prior to this infection coming to light.  This infection took its toll and rooted itself in my dads newly engineered heart, to which it then spread throughout all of his organs. He underwent a 14.5 hour operation which had a 50/50 chance of being successful. Initially it was, his heart had been reconstructed due to a large proportion of it being infected and another two valves being replaced. It would have been more simple to give dad a heart transplant at this point but time wasn't on our side and this 'Commando Procedure' had to take place otherwise the infection would have taken his life. A few days later after this massive heart op, my dad suffered from a bleed on the brain and again it was touch and go as to whether he would survive another major operation after he had had 4 open heart surgeries in a month including a reconstruction. Dad was rushed from the Liverpool Heart and Chest hospital to a specialist Neurological hospital where he had brain surgery to stop the bleed. This was successful, however, my dad suffered a level of brain damage that left him unable to swallow. For the next two weeks dad was being tube fed and more often than not 'asleep' and on a ventilator. After this time the infections and damage that had been done to my dads incredible body was inevitably too much although he was relatively stable. My dads organs began to collapse and fail on the thursday and we said goodbye on the saturday.

The last two months have been a rollercoaster to say that least, but we are taking comfort in knowing he put up such a fight but the odds were against him. He wanted to come home to us so badly, but this wasn't possible. It's a bitter pill to swallow to think dad went into hospital for what was meant to be a 'life enhancing' procedures, but in the end it took his life.

Please donate as much or as little as you'd like to increase the research and experiments into heart diseases across the UK, so as little people have to go through this agony as possible.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
It still doesn’t feel real writing this, and I’m not sure if ever will. Myself, my mum and a few close friends and family are going to be participating in the Winter Walk 2021, walking 13 miles for the British Heart Foundation in honour of my dad, Simon. Who sadly passed away a few weeks ago of an unexpected heart attack. Simon would have wanted nothing more than me to carry on being a trooper for him, so that’s exactly what i’m going to do. I want to raise as much money as possible for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. 

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. If we could help save the lives of even just a few others, we will be over the moon. Nobody should loose a loved one young. It’s thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps and we want to raise as much as we can, we appreciate that times are hard but anything you have would be incredible! 

. Thank you so much.

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

eventName: The Warbling Baubles sing "The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas"
story:
The Warbling Baubles presents ... "The 12 Guide Dogs of Christmas"

Watch our song here:

https://youtu.be/ricVxZHFe-4

We're a group of Guide Dog Owners from around the UK and we've recorded our own rather canine version of "The 12 Days of Christmas", with the help of our faithful hounds (both working and retired).

We recorded the song from our homes in lockdown, and it was arranged and produced by our brilliant Musical Director, Alison Trelfa. The video was compiled by Marie Howarth. Everyone involved in this project is blind, and we did it all ourselves - recording, editing and video production - with the help of computers, screenreaders and other assistive technology. We're really proud of the finished product, so please watch it, then give a donation.

 We're raising money to help the Guide Dogs for the Blind Association support 12 brand new guide dogs this Christmas!

story:
I will be running 31 Miles in 31days January 2021.  As most of you know GOSH Is a massive part of our lives and is Sofia’s second home!

Without the doctors and nurses at GOSH who knows where we would be today. We have our little fighter and we couldn’t be any more grateful for all the hard work from everyone involved at GOSH!

Please help us raise some money to keep this amazing hospital going, every penny counts!

story:
2020 was a horrific year for many- but for some families, COVID-19 (and all that came with it) wasn’t the worst part. During 2020 some families would of also been dealing with their children being extremely poorly.

Becoming a mum myself in 2018, I can’t think of anything more heart wrenching. So small steps, but I’m running 31 miles in January to help fundraise for Great Ormond Street. Please donate any little amount that you can. I’m not a runner, in fact I only took it up during lockdown #1! Thank you! X 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity (GOSH Charity).

I am running this for my daughter Emily & every GOSH patient & parent 💕. If you know me you will know that I am no runner 😂 & am absolutely useless in the cold so this is certainly going to be a challenge for me!!!

Our daughter Emily was admitted to GOSH in September 2014 at 18 months old for 4 months and was diagnosed with a rare genetic disorder. GOSH were amazing and so supportive to our family at this time & I wanted to be able to give something back.

After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

eventName: Running 50 miles in January for Cancer Research
story:
I don’t want to go into my story too much but, I fought for two years to be diagnosed with Melanoma! Nobody believed me and brushed it off as a cyst! I’m one of the lucky ones who is now able to raise awareness and fundraise for such a worthy cause that’s close to my heart. 


First of all I would like to say:

-If you notice something that’s abnormal for you - get it checked. 

-You don’t have to believe your GP, get a second opinion if you wish, and if you can afford it - go private! 

-It might be scary, but it can save your life.. and what would you prefer? Being scared.. or not being here? 


With all of that being said I would like to raise money for the expertise that saved me.. so they can continue to do great research. I will be running 50 miles over the course of January! I am not a runner.. I’m actually not even one for cardio at all. I’ll be amazed if I can run even one mile, but let’s give it a go for such a good cause! 💞

If you are able to give please click ‘add gift aid’ this costs you absolutely nothing. It means Cancer Research UK can claim 25p of every £1 you donate... extra donations for no extra cost!

story:
Thank you for taking the time to visit Margaret's page. 

As a Mum, big Sister, Gran, Great Gran, Aunt, friend, and neighbour, Margaret will be missed by us all.

My fondest memories of Gran are at family parties where she was always the first up to dance and the last-but-one to bed. She knew all the Scottish folk songs and was always such fun to be with. Gran packed a huge amount of living into her 93 years; and always made me feel lucky for the opportunities I've had. She taught me how to knit, sew (but not to cook) and where the best fish and chip shops were. 

We were all so proud of her when she received her veteran's badge for her service in the Women's land army, where she met Hugh. He was a great writer of letters, apparently, as was Margaret. I will miss receiving letters from Gran, especially as they often still came with a £10 Scottish note.

Margaret's service will be on 29 December 2020 at 2.30pm. This will be streamed online for Margaret's family and friends across the world.

Please share your memories with us and consider making a donation to Cancer Research UK, a charity that was important to Gran.

story:
This page is set up in memory of Noel Pullman who died at the grand old age of 94 on 6 December 2020. He had a long and interesting life which included National Service with the RAF in Northern India just after World War Two; several years as a reporter on various newspapers ending up as assistant editor on the Kent and Sussex Courier; various Public Relations Director roles and finally deciding, with our mother Elisabeth, to set up an Antiques business.

They carried on in antiques, including becoming the go to copper and brass specialists on Portobello Road for over 35 years. Noel and Elisabeth enjoyed travelling and managed to visit as far flung places at Antarctica, the Cook Islands, New Zealand, Australia, the US and all over Europe. 

Noel came across cancer himself, as well as his wife and son and many friends over the years; so it is fitting that Cancer Research U.K. might benefit at his passing.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I've decided to run ( depending on how my knees get on) / walk a marathon ( possibly a marathon and a half depending on how well it goes with 2 kids and a dog in tow) for Cancer Research UK. I've decided to raise money for this charity as I have had family and friends be affected by this horrible disease. 

Due to having lipoedema I carry alot of weight on the bottom half of my body ( which no amount of exercise or dieting will remove ) which makes running really hard for me ( and why it affects my knees so bad) however I want to still try and do this!! 

I will be doing this throughout the month of January 

If i can help in some small way by raising some money I feel like I'm honouring those people who have been affected. 

If you could donate a small amount I would be so grateful and if you can share to others around you to help raise as much as possible this would be amazing. 

I'm going to keep this page updated each week with how I've got on. 


Thank you all 🥰

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.        This is in memory of our dad Kev and hope to raise some much needed funds and to give a bit back to the dedicated team of nurses and those who organise such care. Marie Curie nurses (particularly Polly), helped support dad in his hours of need a handful of times which also supported us so we could rest in between night time care for dad. There care and support was amazing. Dad gave regular donations in support of this amazing cause and was a charity close to his heart. Any amount from £1 upover would be greatly appreciated. 

We raised a cash amount of £51 at the funeral service which will be added on before sending. 

Thank you

story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

eventName: Supporting the RNLI in memory of John Coles
story:
My dad loved supporting the RNLI and was a huge advocate for their work. He donated to them for many years, and felt that this charity could always do with more money and support.

Living on the Thames we spent a lot of time with dad enjoying the river, and the annual Boat Race was a big event in our family.

The RNLI are an incredible organisation and we know that my dad would have wanted us to have included them when raising funds in his memory.

RNLI lifeboats in the Ireland protect hundreds of communities through their 24-hour search and rescue service. They rely on the safest, most reliable lifeboats and modern stations to launch from. 
RNLI relies on donations from you the public to continue saving lives at sea and on inland waters - your donation to this page will help support the running of lifeboat stations in Ireland.

charity.description:
We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together. 

That’s why we’re passionate about sharing the planet’s resources more sustainably, tackling climate change and protecting endangered wildlife.

charity.name: WWF-UK
story: IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice theres less wildlife than there used to be. Thats because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

charity.description: Right now, millions of children are in danger. They face violence, disease, hunger and the chaos of war and disaster. Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Please donate what you have spare, even if it 50p. If we all pull together we can make a difference and raise some money for UNICEF.

https://www.google.co.uk/amp/s/news.sky.com/story/amp/covid-19-for-the-first-time-in-its-history-unicef-will-help-feed-kids-in-the-uk-12163515

For the first time in their history UNICEF are helping feed children in the UK. This year has been so hard for so many people.   Can you help?

We launched Willow and Flower this year. The Covid year. And I want to be able to use it to make a difference, if we can. 

Please donate what you can.  Names will be put “into a hat” on Friday evening (18th Dec) and the winner chosen at random. 

Wreath delivery local to Shrewsbury - I’m not sure if it will arrive by Christmas if I post  now.

THANK YOU.

On our own we can’t do much but together we can make a difference. 


Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

Unicef ensures more children get life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection than anyone else. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. unicef.org.uk
charity.name: Unicef UK
story:
Hello friends!

I'm running the Royal Parks Half Marathon in April 2021! Those of you who've known me for a while now are probably thinking, "What??" (and those who've known me for a REALLYYY long time are probably thinking, WHAAAT???) - and yes, when I started running (and enjoying it!) I was also rather shocked... BUT! It's never too late to pick up something new - and reading a bunch of ultrarunning books really helped (Google Scott Jurek! You're welcome).

So one fine morning during Covid lockdown I decided I would run a half marathon! And why not run for a good cause? Hence the decision to run for Unicef. Unicef needs your help to support children around the world. Your donation will help to provide children life-saving food, vaccinations, education and protection. Your donation will make a difference. Please donate what ever you can to my fundraiser for Unicef UK. With your help, we can build a safer world for children. Thank you ~

eventName: The top to the bottom in 24hrs
story: 2020 has been a bad year but it only dawned on me recently that a lot of fundraising for charities is done by people hosting events. Obviously due to covid a lot of these events have not happened. So I decided that I would do what I can to try and raise some money for a good cause. I have chosen unicef as they are a reputable charity that work here in the UK but also all over the world. My challenge quite simply to ride my Motorbike from John O’Groats to Lands End within 24hrs!!! Wish me luck! Any donations no matter how small are greatly appreciated. Many thanks Steve

charity.description: WaterAid is an international not-for-profit, determined to make clean water, decent toilets and good hygiene normal for everyone, everywhere within a generation. Only by tackling these three essentials in ways that last can people change their lives for good.
charity.name: WaterAid
story: We are challenging ourselves to drink nothing but water this January. We are taking on the ultimate detox by avoiding caffeine, alcohol and all other drinks while supporting WaterAid. Give before 4 February 2021 and your donation will be doubled by the UK government, up to £2 million, making double the difference in communities across Ethiopia. Together, we will bring clean water to 50,000 people in Ethiopia and thousands more around the world, helping them change their own lives, forever. If you would like further information about the difference your gift will make and the positive impact it will have on peoples lives, please visit us at www.wateraid.org/uk. Diolch yn fawr, thank you.
